<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>On Safe Zones</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois2.cgi?The RealmWeaver">The RealmWeaver</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 5:46 p.m. 9/2/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> On Safe Zones<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/pvpquest/images/divider.gif" width=452 height=22 border=0></center><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><b>In Reply To:</b> <A HREF="http://www.everworld.net/cgi-local/pvp.cgi?read=427" TARGET=_self>About PvP Editorial</A> (Kain)
</STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#FFFFFF FACE=arial>
<P>I'm not sure why "Safe Zones" are becoming such an issue. I think they are both a necessary and helpful part of a successful PK environment. Note, we are not talking about entire zones or "areas" on the game, we are talking about a very small area, or a single building, or even a single room in a building. There should be places where people can go to chat with friends, hang out, converse, and basically "chill" without worrying about fights breaking out. Two reasons for this: 1) People like to go AFK once in awhile without having to log off. Having a place to sit for awhile while making a sandwhich, taking a smoke break, or going to the bathroom is refreshing and helpful. It's terrible to have to worry about what's happening every time you get up from your chair or glance away from the monitor. What's worse is when you are <i>forced</i> to leave. I remember getting phone calls when MUDding and returning to see "You are dead. R.I.P." Not a good feeling.

<P>Granted, the potential for abuse does exist - but we must weigh the consequences here. With Safe Zones we have the above described benefits, and without there is a small chance for abuse or overuse. I feel that the benefits far outbalance the potential for abuse. If the abuse increases or gets out of hand - steps could be taken to curtail it. For instance, have a "timer" placed on players involved in a PK fight so that they are exempt from the benefits of Safe Zones for 20 minutes or so after being attacked. This prevents two things: 1) people attacking you and then running to a safe zone before revenge can be dealt and 2) you attacking people who flee and hide in a safe zone because they are afraid. Safe Zones are not for hiding from your enemies, there to allow a certain amount of free social interaction without the dread of impending death.
<P>[The RealmWeaver]
<P>dcc5500@rit.edu
<BR>ICQ#: 30795819
<BR>IM: WrldWeaver
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
